      • getWeights

        public static Point getWeights(Point point,
                               java.util.List<Point> computedPoints)
                        throws PrismException
        Returns a point that represents a hyperplane that separates point from computedPoints. An LP solver is used to get the hyperplane, but it is expected that the number of points in computedPoints is relatively small and so this approach should be efficient
        Parameters:
        point - A point which should be at one direction from the separating hyperplane.
        computedPoints - Set of points which should be at the other direction from the separating hyperplane.
        Returns:
        A vector orthogonal to the computed separating hyperplane.
        Throws:
        PrismException - When the LP solver throws an exception or returns an unexpected result, an exception with a related message is thrown.

      • fillDirections

        protected static java.util.Map<Point,Point> fillDirections(java.util.List<Point> computedPoints,
                                                           java.util.List<Point> directions,
                                                           boolean horiz)
        This method takes a list of computed points together with their associated directions, where points are possibly repeated, and returns a map in which to each point from computedPoints corresponds the associated direction from directions which has the most extreme slope. Which extreme is taken depends on the horiz parameter.
        Note that this method considers two points as "equal" if the method isCloseTo(Point) returns true. So the returned map will not contain two keys which are too close to each other, which should be fine w.r.t. roundoff errors, but might theoretically cause trouble if the corner points of the Pareto curve are very close to each other.
        It is guaranteed that if there are two points p1 and p2 in computedPoints such that p1.isCloseTo{p2} is true and p1 occurs in computedPoints before p2, then p1 will be given precedence when picking a representative for the key in the map. This is crucial when using this method together with removeDuplicities(List).
        Parameters:
        computedPoints - The computed points of the Pareto curve
        directions - The directions associated with the computed points.
        horiz - If true, gets the one which is closest to horizontal, if false then the one which is closest to vertical.
        Returns:
        A map in which to each point from computedPoints is associated the most extreme direction from directions.

      • removeDuplicities

        protected static java.util.List<Point> removeDuplicities(java.util.List<Point> list)
        This method takes a list of points and returns a sub-list in which points that are very close to each other (where isCloseTo(Point) is used to determine what is "very close") are removed. The order of elements is preserved. It is guaranteed that if there are two points p1 and p2 in list such that p1.isCloseTo{p2} is true and p1 occurs in list before p2, then p1 will be given precedence when picking the point to keep. This is crucial when using this method together with fillDirections.
        Parameters:
        list -
        Returns:

      • upperBoundPoints

        protected static java.util.List<Point> upperBoundPoints(java.util.List<Point> computedPoints,
                                                        java.util.List<Point> directions)
        This method takes the set of some corner points of a pareto curve computedPoints together with associated orthogonal lines directions that determine current over-approximation, and returns the points which determine the over-approximation. (These points are in fact the intersecting points of the directions which are not covered by other points.)
        Parameters:
        computedPoints - Corner points of the Pareto curve
        directions - Directions (orthogonal lines) associated with the corner points
        Returns:
        The list of points that together with computedPoints determine the over-approximation of the pareto curve

      • getNewTarget

        protected static Point getNewTarget(java.util.List<Point> computedPoints,
                                    java.util.List<Point> directions,
                                    double errorTolerance,
                                    double[] maxValues)
        Returns new point for computation of two dimensional pareto curve. More formally, this method takes the points on the pareto curve computed so far, together with the directions (i.e. orthogonal hyperplanes) corresponding to the points, and returns a point which can still be in a pareto curve, and which is most distant from the points which are already known to be on the pareto curve. Here, most distant means that a point (x,y) is taken such that for every point (a,b) from the pareto curve the number max{x-a,y-b) is maximized.
        Parameters:
        computedPoints - The list of already computed corner points of the pareto curve.
        directions - The list of directions associated with the computed corner points.
        errorTolerance - The required precision of the pareto curve being approximated
        Returns:
        The point, or null if no point has a distance greater than errorTolerance

      • solveEqns

        protected static double[] solveEqns(double[][] eqns,
                                    double[] b)
        Uses Gaussian elimination to solve equations given by eqns and b. The equations are given by eqns.x=b, where eqns is a matrix, and b is a column vector.
        Returns:
        Array containing values for each variable.
